    <title>Combined summary - Making the case for flag day activation of taproot</title>
    <updated>2023-06-14T19:00:19.391388+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-March/018595.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is currently divided over the activation of the Taproot upgrade, with discussions on whether to proceed with a flag day activation or a BIP8 LOT=false deployment. The proposed state machine approach provides a feasible solution that allows for a safer activation process of Taproot. The debate over LOT=true continues in the bitcoin-dev community, with some members opposing the idea of forced signaling while others support it as a means of ensuring activation. One option being debated is BIP8, which allows users to activate a soft fork without miner signaling while also enabling them to abort the process if not enough miners signal for it. However, concerns have been raised about divergent consensus rules on the network if LOT=false is chosen. A proposed alternative is flag day activation, which involves choosing a block height after which the new taproot rules become enforced and eliminating the potential for social media attacks and brinksmanship.Chris Belcher, a Bitcoin developer, proposed flag day activation as an alternative method that removes miners from activation and eliminates the risk of brinksmanship. This method works by choosing a block height after which the new taproot rules become enforced, and it creates an environment where there can be no game of chicken that puts the Bitcoin network at risk. In the recent bitcoin-dev email thread, Russell O'Connor expressed his support for almost any proposed taproot activation method, including a flag day activation. He thinks that starting with BIP8 LOT=false is a reasonably safe activation method and will be viewed as acceptable by the majority of the community.While some believe that flag day activation would take away the power of social media opposition, others argue that it is a legitimate way to prevent brinksmanship and gives users control over the activation process. Ultimately, someone will have to make a decision, and the Bitcoin economy and users will be asked what they think of flag day activation. If it turns out that Core developers do something evil, the community could resist it with a counter-flag-day-activation. The proposed flag day activation has been discussed on the Bitcoin-dev mailing list and is open for feedback and suggestions from the community.The conversation revolves around the activation of Taproot in Bitcoin. While both flag day activation and BIP8 LOT=false deployment have supporters, some are worried that choosing BIP8 LOT=false could lead to divergent consensus rules on the network. To mitigate this concern, a second Core deployment of LOT=true has been suggested, but there are differing opinions on timelines and methods of activation. Some suggest starting with a short signaling period, while others believe a flag day activation from the start would be more effective. Ultimately, there are multiple plausible paths towards activation, and forthcoming PRs will help determine the best approach. The debate highlights the challenges of balancing two important principles: allowing miners to operate on their agreed contract versus protecting against protocol sclerosis for the project as a whole. The author of the article advocates for bringing Taproot to Bitcoin using the proposed activation method and believes that forthcoming PRs will help determine the best approach.</summary>
